---
/**
 * Keep inline tags on one line with outer spaces (Astro whitespace).
 * Never break before <em>/<strong>/<a> after a word.
 */
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Heidegger: Authenticity, Resoluteness, and Being-towards-Death | Foundations | Identity Engineering">
	<main class="min-h-screen">
		<section class="border-b border-white/10 px-6 pt-28 pb-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
				<a href="/foundations" class="mb-6 inline-block text-sm text-white/40 transition hover:text-white/70">
					← Foundations
				</a>
				<div class="text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Foundations · Heidegger</div>
				<h1 class="mt-3 text-5xl font-bold tracking-tighter leading-[0.95] text-white md:text-6xl">
					Authenticity, Resoluteness, and Being-towards-Death
				</h1>
				<p class="mt-6 max-w-2xl text-xl font-light leading-relaxed text-white/50">
					Heidegger does not present a self-help ethic. He analyzes the structure of existence (Dasein), including everyday conformity, finitude, and the possibility of owned commitment.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="px-6 py-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-12 text-lg leading-relaxed text-white/55">
				<div class="rounded-2xl border border-white/10 bg-white/[0.03] p-5 text-base leading-relaxed text-white/60">
					<strong class="text-white/80">Reading protocol on this page:</strong> First Heidegger in his own terms, focused on <em class="text-white/75 not-italic">Being and Time</em>. Then the narrowest possible Identity Engineering reading. No framework-first shortcuts.
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">1 · Dasein and the Structure of Existence</div>
					<p>
						In <em class="text-white/75 not-italic">Being and Time</em> (1927), Heidegger analyzes human existence as <strong class="text-white/80">Dasein</strong>. Dasein is not treated as an object among objects, but as the being for whom its own being is at issue.
					</p>
					<p class="mt-4">
						Two structures matter here: <strong class="text-white/80">thrownness</strong> (facticity we do not choose) and projection (the way we exist toward possibilities). This tension is constitutive, not accidental.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">2 · Authenticity, the They, and Being-towards-Death</div>
					<div class="mb-4 rounded-xl border border-white/10 bg-black/20 p-4 text-sm text-white/60">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Core distinction (Heidegger):</strong> Everyday existence is often absorbed in <em class="text-white/75 not-italic">das Man</em> (“the they,” or “the anyone”). Authenticity names an owned mode of existence in which Dasein takes responsibility for finite possibilities.
					</div>
					<p>
						Being-towards-death is not morbidity. It marks finitude as structurally unavoidable, so choices cannot be postponed indefinitely into anonymous social routine.
					</p>
					<p class="mt-4">
						Resoluteness (<em class="text-white/75 not-italic">Entschlossenheit</em>) is this owned stance: taking up one’s factical situation without the illusion of total control.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">3 · Relevance for Identity Engineering</div>
					<div class="mb-4 rounded-xl border border-cyan-400/20 bg-cyan-400/[0.04] p-4 text-sm text-white/65">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Inspiration from Heidegger:</strong> identity work must account for both situated constraint and projective possibility. Neither pure determinism nor pure voluntarism is adequate.
					</div>
					<div class="mb-4 rounded-xl border border-violet-400/20 bg-violet-400/[0.04] p-4 text-sm text-white/65">
						<strong class="text-white/80">IE additions:</strong> thrownness as boundary condition, resoluteness as operational commitment, and finitude as a practical limiter that forces prioritization.
					</div>
					<ul class="space-y-4">
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Thrownness plus projection:</strong> Any design model starts from non-chosen conditions, then works with explicit possibility selection rather than fantasy reset assumptions.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">The they as default drift:</strong> Unexamined conformity explains why identity can remain functionally coherent yet personally unowned.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Finitude as planning horizon:</strong> Limited time reframes commitments from optional preferences into consequential selections.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Resoluteness as commitment policy:</strong> The key transfer is procedural: fewer anonymous defaults, more owned commitments that survive mood and context shift.
						</li>
					</ul>
					<p class="mt-6">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Differentiation from nearby anchors:</strong> Compared with Sartre, Heidegger emphasizes prior situatedness and inherited intelligibility structures. Compared with Jung, his analysis is less depth-psychological and more ontological-phenomenological.
					</p>
					<p class="mt-4">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Interpretive boundary:</strong> this page does not claim Heidegger directly yields an engineering model. It treats his existential structures as constraints for practical identity design.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 bg-white/[0.015] px-6 py-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-8 text-lg leading-relaxed text-white/55">
				<div>
					<div class="mb-2 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Sources</div>
					<ul class="space-y-2 text-base text-white/50">
						<li>
							Primary (catalog access): Martin Heidegger, <a href="https://openlibrary.org/works/OL77609W/Sein_und_Zeit?edition=key%3A/books/OL7283965M" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-white/70 underline decoration-white/25 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50"><em class="text-white/75 not-italic">Sein und Zeit / Being and Time</em></a> (work-level catalog and editions).
						</li>
						<li>
							Overview (stable archive citation): <a href="https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/spr2026/entries/heidegger/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-white/70 underline decoration-white/25 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50">Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy: “Martin Heidegger” (Spring 2026 archive)</a>.
						</li>
						<li>
							Terminology and citation metadata: <a href="https://plato.stanford.edu/cgi-bin/encyclopedia/archinfo.cgi?entry=heidegger" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-white/70 underline decoration-white/25 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50">SEP author/citation information</a>.
						</li>
					</ul>
				</div>
				<div>
					<div class="mb-2 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Related</div>
					<p>
						Heidegger is the ontological anchor for the modern sequence: he clarifies why identity discourse must include situatedness, temporality, and finite commitment, not only freedom-talk.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 px-6 py-14">
			<div class="mx-auto flex max-w-3xl flex-col gap-4 text-sm sm:flex-row sm:items-center sm:justify-between">
				<a href="/foundations" class="text-white/50 transition hover:text-white/80">← All foundations</a>
				<div class="flex flex-wrap gap-x-6 gap-y-2">
					<a href="/ontology" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Ontology</a>
					<a href="/blog" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Blog</a>
					<a href="/framework" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Framework</a>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>
	</main>
</Layout>
